wah.giovann.csvhandler

Class CSVArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • java.util.ArrayList<CSVRecord>
          • wah.giovann.csvhandler.CSVArray
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<CSVRecord>, Collection<CSVRecord>, List<CSVRecord>, RandomAccess

    public class CSVArray
extends ArrayList<CSVRecord>
    The CSVArray class is a collection CSVRecord objects that represents the contents of at .csv file.

    A CSVArray can be manipulated in a number of ways, such as modifying the header, adding or removing data items or columns, or to sorting based on column names. The CSVArray can then written to file using an instance of the CSVWriter class.

    If a CSVArray instance does not have a header, the use of whats called a dummy header is put into place. With a dummy header, CSV file columns can be referred to by their indices. To check whether a CSVArray has a header, see the hasHeader() method.

    In the normal case, a CSVArray instance is created by a CSVReader using the readCSV method.
    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    Giovann Wah

      • sortBy

        public void sortBy(int columnIndex,
                   boolean numeric,
                   boolean ascendingOrder)
        Sorts the CSVArray records based on their values in the column at index columnIndex. Whether or not the records should be sorted by treating values as numeric or alphanumeric is determined by the boolean numeric. Whether or not the records should be sorted in ascending or descending order is determined by the boolean ascendingOrder.
        Parameters:
        columnIndex - Index of the header column with which records will be sorted.
        numeric - If true, treat the values found at the index columnIndex as numeric. Otherwise, treat them as alphanumeric.
        ascendingOrder - If true, sort the records in ascending order. Otherwise, sort the records in descending order.

Whether or not the records should be sorted in ascending or descending order is determined by the boolean ascendingOrder.

        public void addDummyColumn(int columnIndex)
        If this CSVArray has no header, this method will add a new column at the specified index. All CSVRecord values at that index are initiated to the empty string. If the CSVArray has a header, this method does nothing. The hasHeader() method can be used to check if a CSVArray has a header or not.
        Parameters:
        columnIndex - The index at which to add the new column.
